04358nam a22005655i 9780774890076DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748900767 a10.59962/97807748900762doi  a(DE-B1597)662203  a(OCoLC)970406072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBL2530.C2bB5119 2017 7aSOC0390002bisacsh04a306.6/0971223  aLB 466052rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90561:9821 aBibby, Reginald W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResilient Gods :bBeing Pro-Religious, Low Religious, or No Religious in Canada /cReginald W. Bibby. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b27 figures, 84 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Early Days of God’s Dominion -- tDeclining Religious Participation among Boomers -- tPro-Religion, Low Religion, and No Religion -- tThe Polarized Mosaic -- tReligious Inclinations and Personal Well-Being -- tReligious Inclinations and Social Well-Being -- tReligion versus Spirituality -- tDealing with Death -- tThe Resilience of Religion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAre Canadians becoming less religious? After playing a central role in our lives for nearly a century, religion did seem to be losing its salience in Canada. Many observers saw this trend as inevitable, reflecting secularization patterns seen elsewhere in the Western world. But there is more to the story. Reginald Bibby’s Resilient Gods takes an in-depth look at the religious landscape in Canada today. Pulling together extensive data, he finds that a solid core of some 30 percent continue to embrace religion, while a similar proportion is rejecting it. The remaining 40 percent are somewhere in the middle. The picture that emerges is not one of religious decline but rather of religious polarization, with the numbers of “pro-religious,” “no religious,” and “low religious” in flux. Such proclivities are influenced by social and cultural factors, one being increased immigration, which is ensuring the viability of a pro-religious core. The gods are here to stay, Bibby argues, but so what? Using the most current information available, including unique national survey data, he explores the implications of pro-religious, no-religious, and low-religious choices for personal and social well-being, spirituality, and attitudes towards death. The questions he asks are compelling and the answers thought-provoking whether one embraces the gods or not.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIrreligionxCanada. 0aIrreligionzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077489007640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774890076423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774890076/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles